english:
  title: 'A Record of Travels South: Moonlit Diary'
  author: Lee Kyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I have long desired to wander through distant lands, and whenever my horse's hooves carried me to places of unusual wonder or rare sights, I would gather them in verse and collect them in prose, making them treasures for my later years. Why such care? Should I live to see my legs weaken and my back bend, confined within four walls and the narrow space of my chamber, then taking up this humble collection and seeing the traces of my youthful wanderings—the vigorous journeys and delights of those days—they would appear before me as vividly as yesterday, enough to ease the melancholy of old age.

    In my poetry collection are several poems from the South, and reading them now, those journeys feel as present as if they still lay before my eyes.

    Five years later, I was sent to the provincial service at Jeonju, and in two years of travel through the region, my wanderings were indeed many. Yet whenever rivers and mountains and moonlit breezes drew forth my whistle, administrative duties and legal disputes would rush in to interrupt, leaving me with only scattered couplets and phrases, many unfinished. Thus my complete poems number scarcely more than sixty. Still, the customs and forms of various provinces and their mountains held much worth recording, but what I could not immediately capture in verse, I hastily noted on scraps of paper as a daily record, mixing in local dialects and common speech. When I returned to the capital in the winter of 1195, I brought these notes out to read, only to find them so rough and fragmentary as to be nearly unreadable. Ashamed of my own work, I burned them all. From the ashes, I salvaged a few readable pieces and arrange them here.

    Jeonju, also called Wansan, was the ancient land of Baekje. With its dense population and crowded houses, it retains the spirit of an old kingdom. Its people are neither crude nor ignorant, and its officials carry themselves like refined scholars, their bearing deliberate and dignified. There stands Mount Jungja, most verdant and majestic, the guardian peak of the province. Wansan itself is but a modest summit, yet remarkable that a region should take its name from such a small height.

    A thousand paces from the provincial seat stands Gyeongbok Temple, which houses the legendary Flying Abbot's Room. I had heard of it long ago but never found time to visit until a day of leisure allowed me to go. This Flying Abbot's Room, it is said, was carried here long ago by the Great Bodhisattva Bodeok from Banryong Mountain. The Bodhisattva, known as Jibop, once dwelt at Yeonbok Temple on Banryong Mountain in Goguryeo. One day he told his disciples: "Goguryeo honors only Daoism and spurns the Buddha's teaching. This kingdom cannot endure. Where might we find safety from calamity?" His disciple Myeongdeok replied: "Mount Godal in Jeonju is a place of eternal peace." On the third day of the third month in the second year of Jianfeng, a rabbit year, when Myeongdeok opened the door, the hall had already moved to Mount Godal, more than a thousand li from Banryong. Myeongdeok lamented: "Though this mountain is sublime, its waters have dried. Had I known the Master would move here, I would have brought the ancient spring." The scholar Choe Chiwon has written a detailed account of this marvel, so I merely note it here.

    On the twenty-ninth day of the twelfth month, I began to tour the subject counties. Maryeong and Jinan are ancient settlements in mountain valleys, their people simple and rustic, their faces like those of gibbons, their food smelling of raw flesh with the manner of barbarians. When reproved, they started like frightened deer, ready to bolt. Following winding mountain paths, I reached Yunje. From there to Gosan, the peaks grew perilous, the summits towering ten thousand cubits high, the paths so narrow one must dismount. Gosan proved not unwelcoming compared to other regions. From there I went to Yeyang, then to Nangsan, staying but one night in each place.

    The next day I headed toward Geumma County seeking what the people call the "support stones"—ancient megaliths said to have been set by sages of old, remarkable for their strange legends. Entering Seong, I found the county nearly emptied of people, the fences fallen silent. Even the inn was thatched, and only four or five officials came to receive me. The sight wounded my heart.

    In the twelfth month, by imperial decree, I was tasked with harvesting timber from Byeonsan, the timber depot of our realm. Though we have cut here year after year for palace construction, trees thick as ox-hides and tall as heaven are never exhausted. Since I was charged with overseeing the work, they called me the "Timber Master." On the road I composed a jest in verse:

    *Authority sits humble as a porter,
    Honor befits the woodcutter's shame.*

    In the first month of the rabbit year, I entered Byeonsan for the first time. Peaks rose and fell in endless succession, their slopes folding and unfolding—I could not tell how many li stretched before me. Below, the great sea lay bare, and within it clustered isles: Gunsan, Hedgehog Island, and Dove Island, all within a day's journey. The fishermen said: "With a fair wind, swift as an arrow's flight, China lies not far." The mountain abounded with chestnuts, which the locals harvest yearly for sustenance.

    Walking further, beautiful groves of bamboo stood thick as hemp, growing for hundreds of paces before being fenced. Crossing the bamboo thicket, I descended to open road and came upon Boan, a county where the tides transform flat paths into seas. One must wait for the waters to recede before passing. When I first journeyed there, the tide was coming in, still fifty paces away. I spurred my horse forward, eager to outrun it, but my servant cried out in alarm and seized my bridle. I would not listen and kept riding. Soon the waters came crashing down with terrifying force, like ten thousand armies rushing at speed, their roar so dreadful I lost my wits. I fled toward the mountain, barely escaping as the floodwaters reached my horse's flanks.

    The sight was marvelous: blue waves and green peaks appearing and disappearing, the light shifting from clear to cloudy, morning to evening, each moment bringing new beauty. Above floated clouds and rosy mists in ever-changing hues, layered like a thousand-fold painted screen. I gazed upon it and lamented not having two or three poet-friends to ride beside me composing verses in harmony. Yet the landscape so stirred my spirit that unthinking, poems flowed unbidden from my lips.

    Once, passing Master's Port, the bright moon rose above the ridge, illuminating the sandy flats with silvery radiance. The mood was exquisitely fresh. I loosened my reins and gazed across the green sea ahead, lost in recitation for a long while. My groom wondered at my lingering. From that moment, I composed a poem.

    In the leap twelfth month, I again received imperial orders to investigate grievances in various counties, first directing my path to Jinrye. The mountain rose so steeply and the way grew so obscure that I felt as if I had stepped into another realm. My spirit grew melancholy and weary. Only after midday did I reach the county seat, but finding both the magistrate and officers absent, I settled into waiting. Around the second watch of night, both came galloping from eight thousand paces away, breathless and urgent. They tethered their horses without food or water—for horses ridden so hard will otherwise perish. I feigned sleep but heard them, and knowing their sincerity toward this old traveler, I consented to accept their hospitality. A courtesan played the lute beautifully. I, who had drunk nothing in other counties, drank deeply here and listened to the music. Perhaps the far journey and strange lands had made me sentimental, touched by every sight.

    From Jinrye I traveled to Namwon, ancient seat of Daebang. Behind its inn stood a bamboo pavilion, spacious and lovely. I rested one night and departed.

    In spring of the rabbit year's third month, I traveled waterways inspecting boats. Every fishing village and salt market I visited, every waterway I surveyed. I went to Mangyeong, Limpi, and Okgu, lingering several days before heading toward Jangsa. Along the way stood a rock bearing a carved Maitreya image, sublime and radiant. Beyond it, a great hollow stone invited entry. Passing through, the space widened suddenly, the ceiling opened to sky, revealing a magnificent temple ornate and bright—Doseul Temple. As dusk approached, I rode swiftly to Seonun Temple to rest.

    Next morning I entered Jangsa, and from there to Musong—both fallen counties offering nothing memorable, merely the tedious inspection of boats and counting of vessels. I reflected: in former days, a single spring or small pond had delighted me beyond measure, for I yearned for great waters yet had not seen them. Now, long acquainted with the sea, all before my eyes is water, and all that fills my ears is its roaring voice. Already I have grown weary of the sight. Why does Heaven feed mortals so hastily that the starving suddenly gorge themselves and loathe even sweetness?

    On the twentieth day of the eighth month, I marked the anniversary of my father's death. The day before, I journeyed to Solae Temple on Byeonsan. Upon the wall hung poems of the late Scholar Jayeon. I composed two verses in response and inscribed them.

    The next day, with Magistrate Yi of Buryeong and six or seven other companions, I climbed to Wonhyo's Room. A wooden ladder, dozens of stories high, rose dizzingly upward. Treading carefully, foot by foot, I reached the terrace and chamber perched among the treetops. Local legend tells of tigers and leopards that attempted to climb here but could not reach. Beside it stood a small hermitage said to be where the sage of the Snake Bower once dwelt. When Wonhyo came to dwell here, the Snake Bower also came to attend him. They wished to brew tea for him, but finding no spring, suddenly water burst forth from the rocky crevice—sweet as milk—providing water for their tea ever after.

    Wonhyo's Room is but eight feet across, inhabited by a single aged monk with bushy brows and tattered robes bearing an air of ancient dignity. He had divided the space into inner and outer chambers. The inner held Buddhist images and Wonhyo's portrait; the outer contained merely a jar, a pair of shoes, a tea set, a scripture stand—no kitchen, no attendants. He ate but one meal daily, taken at Solae Temple below.

    My attendant whispered to me: "This master once dwelt in Jeonju, behaving arrogantly wherever he went, troubling all who knew him. Then he vanished. Now I recognize him—it is he." I sighed and reflected: "Those of common station remain fixed in their nature, unable to transform. But those whose evil startles others possess uncommon capacity. When such a one turns toward goodness, their rise becomes extraordinary and sublime. Of old, a hunting general met the Bodhisattvas Ushit and Daiboku, reformed his ways, and became a sage of great virtue. And in these lands, the Great Bodhisattva Myeongdeok, though a falconer, became the high disciple of the Great Sage Bodeok. By such reasoning, that this master should break his former habits and assume extraordinary practice occasions no surprise."

    I then asked to see the legendary Inconceivable Abbot's Room. When shown, it proved ten thousand times more perilous than Wonhyo's. A wooden ladder a hundred feet high clung directly to a sheer cliff, with bottomless chasms on three sides. One must count each step to descend to the chamber, and a single misstep means certain death. In my youth, merely ascending a modest pavilion of a few fathoms would make my head swim and prevent me from looking down. Here, before even entering, my legs trembled and my vision blurred. Yet having long heard of this marvel and journeyed expressly to witness it, to depart without seeing both the chamber and paying respects before the True Icon of Great Master Bodeok would bring lifelong regret. I hesitated, then slowly crept downward, my feet upon the rungs while my body seemed already falling. At last I entered.

    Striking flint to light a flame, I burned incense and bowed before the True Icon of Master Jincheok. The master, named Bodeok, hailed from Daebingon Village in Byeogol County. At twelve years old, he came to dwell in the Inconceivable Cave on Hyungyae Mountain—which is this very place. Through deep meditation, he sought to perceive Maitreya and Ksitigarbha Bodhisattva, yet for days neither appeared. In despair, he cast himself into the abyss. Two celestial youths caught him in their hands, saying: "Your dharmic power is weak; therefore the two sages do not manifest. Strive harder." Renewed in effort, on the twenty-first day, beneath a tree before the cave, both Bodhisattvas appeared in form, bestowed the precepts, and gave him the Divination Scripture in two volumes and one hundred ninety-nine tokens as guides to enlightenment. The chamber itself was anchored by iron chains driven into the rock, preventing it from tilting—local tradition attributes this to the work of the Sea Dragon.

    As I prepared to depart, the magistrate spread wine upon a summit, saying: "This is the Sea-Gazing Terrace. I wish to refresh your spirit. I have had seats prepared; please rest a moment." I climbed and beheld the great sea surrounding us, the shore mere hundreds of paces distant. With each cup and verse, all the landscape revealed its beauty. Not a trace of worldly concern remained. Light as one shedding mortal form for wings, I felt myself soaring beyond the six directions, reaching up as if to beckon the immortals themselves. All ten of us at table grew intoxicated, though in observance of my father's death, no music played.

    Of all the places I visited, I recorded only those worth noting. Considering the capital as the body and the provinces as its limbs, I traveled merely one limb's outer edge of the southern reaches. And this record itself is but fragments, omissions, and rough sketches—hardly worthy as a legacy for my declining years. Yet I preserve it, awaiting the day when I shall have wandered completely through all directions, gathered complete accounts of my travels, and bound them into a single volume to comfort my old age free from care. Would that not be worthwhile?

    Written this third month of the rabbit year.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Jeonju (全州), also called Wansan (完山), was an important provincial center in medieval Korea, seat of the Later Baekje kingdom in the Three Kingdoms period.
  - key: ''
    value: The Flying Abbot's Room legend reflects Korean Buddhist hagiography, likely influenced by Chinese miraculous tale traditions. Bodhisattva Bodeok is a semi-legendary figure from Goguryeo.
  - key: ''
    value: The Inconceivable Room (不思議方丈) refers to a remote mountain hermitage, emphasizing the miraculous and dangerous nature of the location.
  - key: ''
    value: Scholar-official Choe Chiwon (崔致遠, 857-910) was the most celebrated literary figure of Unified Silla, known for his Buddhist and Daoist learning.
  - key: ''
    value: The meditation practice described involving Maitreya (Miryeok in Korean) and Ksitigarbha (Jijang) reflects Korean Buddhist practice of seeking divine visions through ascetic discipline.
  - key: ''
    value: Yi Gyubo's self-conscious reflection on the transience of pleasure—growing weary of the sea after long exposure—demonstrates the Confucian-Buddhist philosophical sensibility of medieval Korean literati regarding the flux of experience.
